{{Infobox mountain | name = Loloru | photo = | photo_caption = | elevation_m = 1,887 | elevation_ref = | prominence = | location = [[Bougainville Island|Bougainville]], [[Papua New Guinea]] | coordinates = {{coord|6|31|S|155|37|E|type:mountain}} | map = Papua New Guinea | topo = | type = [[Pyroclastic shield]] | age = | last_eruption = 1050 BCE (?) | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
'''Loloru''' is a [[pyroclastic shield]] [[volcano]] located in the southern region of [[Bougainville Island]], within the [[Autonomous Region of Bougainville]] of northeastern [[Papua New Guinea]].
The volcano's summit consists of two nested [[caldera]]s, with an [[andesitic]] [[lava dome]].
==Lake Loloru== [[File:Lake Loloru.jpg|thumb|left|Traditionally sacred Lake Loloru, a [[crater lake]].]] [[File:Buin and Siwai boys visiting Lake Loloru and feeling discomfort.jpg|thumb|Boys from [[Buin, Papua New Guinea|Buin]] and Siwai visiting Lake Loloru (1978).]] '''Lake Loloru''', a crescent-shaped [[crater lake]], is within the volcano. It is a sacred place of South Bougainvillians, who traditionally believe the souls of their dead go here upon death.
