{{Infobox company | name = Sinovel Wind (Group) Co., Ltd. | native_name = 华锐风电科技(集团)股份有限公司 | logo = Sinovel logo.png | logo_size = 200px | type = [[Limited company]] | traded_as = {{sse|601558}} | key_people = | industry = [[Wind power industry|Wind power]] | products = [[Wind turbine]]s | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | num_employees = | | foundation = {{Start date|2004}} ([[Beijing]]) | location = [[Beijing]], [[People's Republic of China]] | homepage = [https://web.archive.org/web/20101220143122/http://www.sinovel.com/en/index.aspx Official Website] {{en icon}} }}
'''Sinovel Wind Group Company''' ({{zh|c=华锐风电}}) is a Chinese [[wind turbine]] manufacturer headquartered in [[Beijing]]. It is the largest wind turbine manufacturer in [[People's Republic of China|China]] and by 2011 market share the second largest in the world.<ref>BTM Consult</ref>
The company aims to be the largest turbine maker by 2015 with half of sales for foreign markets.<ref name=autogenerated1>https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/16/business/energy-environment/16windside.html?_r=1&ref=china</ref>
[[Donghai Bridge Wind Farm]], the first offshore [[wind farm]] in China, began operation in July 2010 using 34 3 [[Watt|MW]] Sinovel turbines.
In December 2010, the [[Massachusetts Water Resources Authority]] ordered a 1.5 MW wind turbine to power a wastewater pumping station in [[Massachusetts Water Resources Authority|Charlestown]], [[Boston]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />
==Controversies== The firm was accused and found guilty of stealing software from [[American Superconductor|AMSC]] and was embroiled in a lawsuit with that firm.<ref name="lawsuit_amsc">[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-09/amsc-taking-sinovel-infringement-suit-to-china-s-supreme-court.html http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-09/amsc-taking-sinovel-infringement-suit-to-china-s-supreme-court.html].</ref><ref>http://investigations.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/08/06/19566531-chinese-firm-paid-insider-to-kill-my-company-american-ceo-says</ref> On 27 June 2013, the [[United States Department of Justice]] declared Sinovel and three Individuals were charged with theft of trade secrets.<ref>http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/2013/June/13-crm-730.html</ref> On 24 January 2018 a U.S. federal jury in [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]], Wisconsin found Sinovel guilty of stealing trade secrets from AMSC causing the American company to lose over US$800 million. Prosecutors stated that Sinovel stole [[trade secrets]] and copyrighted information with the intention of building its own versions of AMSC systems and retrofit previously built wind turbines so it could avoid having to pay AMSC for its technology.<ref name="Verdict">{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sinovel-wind-gro-usa-court/chinas-sinovel-convicted-in-u-s-of-trade-secret-theft-idUSKBN1FD2XL?il=0 |title=China's Sinovel convicted in U.S. of trade-secret theft |date=24 January 2018| website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> The federal judge ordered Sinovel to pay $59 Million for the act of stealing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/npr-judge-orders-chinese-wind-turbine-maker-to-pay-59-million-for-stealing-trade-secrets/|title=Judge Orders Chinese Wind-Turbine Maker To Pay $59 Million For Stealing Trade Secrets|last=Zarroli|first=Jim|website=www.opb.org|language=en|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref> According to a press release by AMSC on 03 July 2018, AMSC has settled the lawsuit with Sinovel.
