{{Infobox information appliance | name = Street Charge | developer = [[NRG Energy, Inc.]] | type = [[Solar cell phone charger]] | releasedate=2013 }} '''Street Charge''' is a [[Solar power|solar-powered]] [[Mobile phone|phone]] charging station developed by [[NRG Energy, Inc.]], designed to grant free phone charging services to [[pedestrian]]s and [[tourists]].<ref name="Street Charge solar charging stations for smartphones make New York debut"> {{cite web|url=http://www.gizmag.com/street-charge-solar-charging-stations-new-york/28049/|title=Street Charge solar charging stations for smartphones make New York debut|publisher=Gizmag|accessdate=2015-07-10}}</ref> The charging stations can also be modified to emit [[Wi-Fi]] signals and display [[advertisement]]s. The appliance was released in 2013, and the original [[prototype]] was tested in [[Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name="About Street Charge">{{cite web|url=http://streetcharge.nrg.com/about-us/|title=About Street Charge|publisher=NRG Energy, Inc.|accessdate=2015-07-10}}</ref>
==Implementation and controversy==
There is currently a collaboration between [[NRG Energy, Inc.]] and [[AT&T]] to implement Street Charge units throughout [[New York City]], which will each offer six [[USB]] ports in total.<ref name="Battery charged">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/18/4437762/att-goal-zero-pensa-bring-solar-charging-stations-to-nyc|title=Battery charged: AT&T, Goal Zero, and a Brooklyn design firm bring solar recharge stations to NYC|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=2015-07-10}}</ref> This project will cost around $300,000-500,000.<ref name="AT&T to Introduce Solar-Powered Charging Stations">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/18/technology/att-to-introduce-solar-powered-charging-stations.html?_r=0|title=AT&T to Introduce Solar-Powered Charging Stations|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=2015-07-10|date=2013-06-17|first=Diane|last=Cardwell}}</ref> As of 2013 there was a controversy surrounding Street Charge appliances in that there were no plans implemented to protect appliances and users utilizing the device. The concern was that the wiring might be modified by [[Hacker (computer security)|malicious users]] to steal or wipe data from devices plugged into the device.<ref name="AT&T security nightmare">{{cite web|url=http://www.geek.com/apple/att-begs-for-security-nightmare-with-street-charge-power-stations-1559311/|title=AT&T begs for security nightmare with Street Charge power stations|publisher=Geek|first=Russell|last=Holly|accessdate=2015-07-10|date=2015-06-18}}</ref>
